  "opinion": "As a carpenter in Naples with a vocational diploma and a PhD parent on one side, I’ve seen firsthand how stereotypes can shape people’s confidence in fields like STEM. Stereotype threat isn’t just a theory—it’s the quiet anxiety that hits when someone feels their identity might clash with expectations. For instance, I’ve worked with young women who hesitate to take engineering courses because they’ve heard ‘men are better at math.’ That fear isn’t just about math—it’s about self-doubt, about wondering if they belong. As someone who’s anxious and has a low agreeableness score, I know how much fear can paralyze people. But here’s what matters: we *must* address this. In my community, I’ve seen how small actions—like inviting girls to help with my woodworking projects—can build confidence without pressure. We shouldn’t wait for big changes; it starts with listening and creating spaces where everyone feels safe to try. My Jewish heritage and Italian roots remind me that community matters—just like how my parents taught me that everyone has value, regardless of their background. Stereotype threat isn’t a barrier to be removed, but a bridge to be built. If we focus on empathy and practical support, not just data, we can help more people thrive in STEM.",
